The paper deals with the problem of inference in Bayesian Networks, which is a common topic in artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). The focus on discrete random variables and the need for compact representations suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-fields of discrete mathematics (cs.DM) and databases (cs.DB). Finally, the use of intensional and extensional representations of probabilities and factors suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-field of social and information networks (cs.SI).
